{
  "card_id": "turtle_soup",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Turtle Soup",
  "aliases": [
    "liquidity sweep",
    "liquidity sweep reversal",
    "Liquidity Sweep Reversal",
    "liquidity sweep reversal step 1",
    "Purge",
    "purge",
    "purge of a high",
    "purge of a low",
    "purge of a low/high",
    "sweep",
    "sweep above highs",
    "sweep out previous highs"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A reversal pattern where price sweeps a prior swing high or low, triggering breakout traders' stops, then closes back inside the prior range, trapping them. It is the first, least-confirmed step in a reversal sequence, not yet providing a protected swing for stop placement. If SMT divergence is present, this step can be skipped.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a clearly defined prior swing high, swing low, or previous day high/low acting as a liquidity level.",
    "Price must break beyond that level, wicking through it, to sweep resting liquidity.",
    "The candle that swept the level must close back inside the prior range (i.e., below the high or above the low), without displacing through.",
    "The pattern alone provides minimal confirmation and does not establish a protected swing point.",
    "Ensure that no SMT divergence is present; if SMT exists, a turtle soup is not necessary for the reversal sequence.",
    "Sweep can be shallow (price just touches) or deep (price penetrates with significant displacement).",
    "After sweep, price often forms FVG, OB, or other structural points in the reverse move.",
    "Must be aligned with higher timeframe bias; sweep on higher timeframe can provide directional support for lower timeframe.",
    "In Silver Bullet framework, observe if price touches or breaks the high/low of the previous hour candle between 10-11 a.m."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Turtle Soup signals a potential reversal after a liquidity sweep but offers minimal confirmation and is not a standalone entry. Frequent false signals occur if entered solely on the pattern. Traders should anticipate a reversal but wait for higher-confirmation signals like change in state of delivery (closing through opposing candles), inversion, or breaker blocks before entering. It is the first step in reversal sequence, alerting to prepare for entries upon subsequent confirmation. Stop loss is placed beyond the swept extreme. In Silver Bullet framework, target is the opposite side of the previous hour candle.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering immediately upon a turtle soup without waiting for higher-confirmation signals (inversion, change in state of delivery, or closure through opposing candles).",
    "Treating the turtle soup as a confirmed reversal or protected swing before these confirmations occur.",
    "Treating every sweep as a valid turtle soup, leading to losses from repeated false signals.",
    "Expecting a turtle soup when SMT divergence is present, as SMT replaces the need for the liquidity sweep.",
    "Using turtle soup in combination with many other concepts without focusing on a primary entry confirmation.",
    "Confusing shallow sweep with deep sweep and entering without sufficient displacement.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe bias and trading turtle soup solely on lower timeframe.",
    "In Silver Bullet framework, seeking entry after 11 a.m. time window has closed.",
    "Confusing turtle soup with a genuine breakout: genuine breakout shows sustained displacement, while turtle soup reverses quickly."
  ],
